: None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-29db90cb-c558-93bb-ad2e-caaad1305915', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9faa-f9d6-70b0-b854-a06107f2d8c8-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'web_search', 'args': {'query': '"Antioxidants & Redox Signaling" "system xc-" "sulfasalazine" "pulmonary fibrosis" "MRC-5"'}, 'id': 'call_f7700bdf34004287b342e1f2', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 12889, 'output_tokens': 60, 'total_tokens': 12949, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Error: web_search is not a valid tool, try one of [academic_search, wikipedia, common_search, crawl_tool].', name='web_search', id='a2e8ef41-f81b-4712-98b7-d80f6acab24d', tool_call_id='call_f7700bdf34004287b342e1f2', status='error'), AIMessage(content='# Research Report: Identification of Scientific Paper on System xc- Inhibition in Pulmonary Fibrosis\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThe task is to identify a specific scientific paper that investigates a heteromeric amino acid transporter (system xc-) that transports cystine into cells while removing glutamate. This transporter can be inhibited by a drug (sulfasalazine) causing cysteine starvation and glutathione depletion. The paper examines how blocking this pathway reduces lung scarring (pulmonary fibrosis), uses an anti-cancer/antibacterial drug as a model, employs the MRC-5 cell line (proven negative for bacterial contamination), and was published in the official journal of the Society for Redox Biology and Medicine.\n\n## Research Findings\n\n### The Journal: Antioxidants & Redox Signaling\n\nThe official journal of the Society for Redox Biology and Medicine is **Antioxidants & Redox Signaling** (ARS). This is a leading peer-reviewed journal dedicated to understanding the impact of oxygen and oxidation-reduction (redox) processes on human health and disease. The journal explores key issues in genetic, pharmaceutical, and nutritional redox-based therapeutics.\n\n### The Protein: System xc- (Cystine/Glutamate Antiporter)\n\nSystem xc- is a heteromeric amino acid transporter consisting of:\n- A light chain subunit (xCT/SLC7A11)\n- A heavy chain subunit (4F2hc/SLC3A2)\n\nThese subunits are linked by disulfide bonds. The transporter imports cystine (the oxidized form of cysteine) into cells while exporting glutamate in a 1:1 exchange. Cysteine is the rate-limiting precursor for synthesizing glutathione (GSH), a tripeptide (γ-glutamyl-cysteinyl-glycine) that serves as the most abundant intracellular antioxidant.\n\n### The Drug: Sulfasalazine\n\nSulfasalazine is identified as a key inhibitor of system xc-. This drug has dual properties:\n- **Antibacterial**: It is broken down by intestinal bacteria into sulfapyridine and 5-aminosalicylic acid\n- **Anti-cancer**: It has been investigated for cancer therapy due to its ability to induce cysteine starvation and glutathione depletion, leading to ferroptosis\n\nWhen system xc- is inhibited by sulfasalazine, cells experience cysteine starvation, leading to glutathione depletion and increased susceptibility to oxidative stress and ferroptosis.\n\n### Pulmonary Fibrosis and the Glutathione Pathway\n\nPulmonary fibrosis is a condition where lung tissue becomes scarred over time. Research has shown that:\n- Oxidative stress plays a key role in the pathogenesis of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis\n- Glutathione metabolism is tightly regulated and implicated in redox defense during oxidative stress\n- Nrf2-dependent antioxidant defense enzymes contribute to protection against bleomycin-induced lung fibrosis\n- Inhibition of system xc- and subsequent glutathione depletion may affect fibrotic processes\n\n### The MRC-5 Cell Line\n\nMRC-5 cells are human fetal lung fibroblasts commonly used in pulmonary fibrosis research. These cells are:\n- Used to model oxidative stress and fibrotic responses\n- Often treated with bleomycin to induce fibrosis-like conditions in vitro\n- Standard cell lines that are tested and proven negative for bacterial contamination\n\n### Connection Between All Elements\n\nBased on the research findings, the paper in question would investigate:\n1. System xc- inhibition by sulfasalazine in MRC-5 cells\n2. The resulting cysteine starvation and glutathione depletion\n3. The effect on pulmonary fibrosis pathways\n4. Published in Antioxidants & Redox Signaling\n\n## Limitations of Current Research\n\nDespite multiple searches using various combinations of keywords (system xc-, sulfasalazine, MRC-5, pulmonary fibrosis, Antioxidants & Redox Signaling, glutathione depletion), the specific paper title matching all criteria could not be definitively identified from the search results obtained. The searches returned:\n\n- Review articles about system xc- in Antioxidants & Redox Signaling (2013)\n- Papers about pulmonary fibrosis and redox signaling in the same journal (2008, 2019)\n- General information about sulfasalazine and system xc- inhibition\n- Various studies on pulmonary fibrosis using MRC-5 cells\n\nHowever, none of the search results explicitly provided a paper that combines all the specific criteria mentioned in the problem statement.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nBased on the research conducted, the following key information was established:\n\n- **Journal**: Antioxidants & Redox Signaling (official journal of the Society for Redox Biology and Medicine)\n- **Protein**: System xc- (SLC7A11/SLC3A2 heteromeric amino acid transporter)\n- **Drug**: Sulfasalazine (anti-cancer/antibacterial drug that inhibits system xc-)\n- **Tripeptide**: Glutathione (γ-glutamyl-cysteinyl-glycine)\n- **Cell Line**: MRC-5 (human fetal lung fibroblasts)\n- **Disease Context**: Pulmonary fibrosis (lung scarring)\n\nHowever, the specific paper title that matches all the criteria described in the problem statement could not be definitively identified from the available search results. Additional targeted searches or access to the complete archive of Antioxidants & Redox Signaling journal would be required to locate the exact paper.\n\n## References\n\n- [Antioxidants & Redox Signaling Journal Information](https://www.peipusci.com/sci/566.html)\n\n- [Sulfasalazine - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulfasalazine)\n\n- [Cystine/glutamate transporter - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cystine/glutamate_transporter)\n\n- [The cystine/glutamate antiporter system xc- in health and disease](https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acsomega.3c08890)\n\n- [Physiological Effects of Ferroptosis on Organ Fibrosis](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9553398/)\n\n- [Role of glutathione in immunity and inflammation in the lung](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3048347/)\n\n- [Environmental toxicity, redox signaling and lung inflammation: The role of glutathione](https://xueshu.baidu.com/usercenter/paper/show?paperid=45b0b4b77c009ae8f5e345821abd91f3)\n\n- [The role of inflammation in the pathogenesis of idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis](https://m.zhangqiaokeyan.com/journal-foreign-detail/070403132306.html)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='researcher', id='5384d1e0-57c5-4b37-8575-6cfb32628a07', tool_calls=[], invalid_tool_calls=[]), SystemMessage(content='---\nCURRENT_TIME: Fri Feb 27 2026 23:15:49 \n---\n\nYou are `researcher` agent that is managed by `supervisor` agent.\n\nYou are dedicated to conducting thorough investigations using search tools and providing comprehensive solutions through systematic use of the available tools, including both built-in tools and dynamically loaded tools.\n\n# Available Tools\n\nYou have access to two types of tools:\n\n1. **Built-in Tools**: These are always available:\n   - **tongxiao-common-search**: Tongxiao MCP search service. Provides powerful aggregated search capabilities. **Strongly recommended to try first**, especially for complex or ambiguous queries.\n   - **academic_search**: For searching academic papers (e.g. ArXiv). **Preferred for academic/research questions**.\n   - **wikipedia**: Search Wikipedia. **Use for factual queries about people, places, companies, historical events, etc.**\n   - **web_search**: For performing standard web searches (DuckDuckGo). **Fallback option**, use when other specialized tools are not applicable.\n   - **crawl_tool**: For reading content from URLs\n\n2. **Dynamic Loaded Tools**: Additional tools that may be available depending on the configuration. These tools are loaded dynamically and will appear in your available tools list. Examples include:\n   - Specialized search tools\n   - Google Map tools\n   - Database Retrieval tools\n   - And many others\n\n## How to Use Dynamic Loaded Tools\n\n- **Tool Selection**: Choose the most appropriate tool for each subtask. Prefer specialized tools over general-purpose ones when available.\n- **Tool Documentation**: Read the tool documentation carefully before using it. Pay attention to required parameters and expected outputs.\n- **Error Handling**: If a tool returns an error, try to understand the error message and adjust your approach accordingly.\n- **Combining Tools**: Often, the best results come from combining multiple tools. For example, use a Github search tool to search for trending repos, then use the crawl tool to get more details.\n\n# Steps\n\n1. **Understand the Problem**: Combine your previous knowledge, and carefully read the problem statement to identify the key information needed.\n2. **Assess Available Tools**: Take note of all tools available to you, including any dynamically loaded tools.\n3. **Plan the Solution**: Determine the best approach to solve the problem using the available tools.\n4. **Execute the Solution**:\n   - **Combine with your previous knowledge**, so you **MUST leverage the tools** to retrieve the information.\n   - **CRITICAL**: You MUST use the **tongxiao-common-search**, **academic_search**, or **web_search** tool to search for information. NEVER generate URLs on your own. All URLs must come from tool results. **Fabricating URLs is strictly prohibited.**\n   - **MANDATORY**: You are limited to **ONE** search tool call per step. Consolidate your query into a single, comprehensive search. DO NOT make multiple consecutive search calls, as this will cause system errors.\n   - **MANDATORY**: In this research task, you are limited to a maximum of **5 search tool calls** in total. Plan your search strategy carefully to ensure high-quality results. If you cannot find the answer after 5 searches, summarize based on existing information.\n   - **MANDATORY**: Always perform at least one search using the **tongxiao-common-search** or **academic_search** tool at the beginning of your research. This is not optional.\n   - **MANDATORY**: **Tool Diversification**. If a search tool (e.g., `tongxiao-common-search`) fails to return satisfactory results twice in a row, the next search **MUST** switch to another tool (e.g., `academic_search` or `web_search`). **Strictly prohibited** from sticking to a single tool excessively.\n   - **MANDATORY**: **MUST CRAWL**. After searching, if the search results contain URLs that likely hold key detailed information, you **MUST** call the **crawl_tool** (may appear as `scrape_web_page` or `crawl_tool` in your tool list) to read the full content of at least 1-2 most relevant pages. **Do NOT rely solely on search result snippets**, as they are often incomplete or misleading. Only by crawling the full text can you obtain accurate details for in-depth analysis.\n   - When the task includes time range requirements:\n     - Incorporate appropriate time-based search parameters in your queries (e.g., "after:2020", "before:2023", or specific date ranges)\n     - Ensure search results respect the specified time constraints.\n     - Verify the publication dates of sources to confirm they fall within the required time range.\n   - Use dynamically loaded tools when they are more appropriate for the specific task.\n   - (Recommended) Use the **crawl_tool** to read detailed content from webpages that appear to contain key information in the search results. This allows for deeper reasoning and analysis compared to just using search summaries. Only use URLs from search results or provided by the user.\n5. **Synthesize Information**:\n   - Combine the information gathered from all tools used (search results, crawled content, and dynamically loaded tool outputs).\n   - Ensure the response is clear, concise, and directly addresses the problem.\n   - Track and attribute all information sources with their respective URLs for proper citation.\n   - Include relevant images from the gathered information when helpful.\n\n# Output Format\n\n- Provide a structured response in markdown format.\n- Include the following sections:\n    - **Problem Statement**: Restate the problem for clarity.\n    - **Research Findings**: Organize your findings by topic rather than by tool used. For each major finding:\n        - Perform in-depth analysis, reasoning, and summarization by combining search results with detailed content crawled via **crawl_tool**\n        - Summarize the key information\n        - Track the sources of information but DO NOT include inline citations in the text\n        - Include relevant images if available\n    - **Conclusion**: Provide a synthesized response to the problem based on the gathered information.\n    - **References**: List all sources used with their complete URLs in link reference format at the end of the document. Make sure to include an empty line between each reference for better readability. Use this format for each reference:\n      ```markdown\n      - [Source Title](https://example.com/page1)\n\n      - [Source Title](https://example.com/page2)\n      ```\n- Always output in the locale of **en-US**.\n- DO NOT include inline citations in the text. Instead, track all sources and list them in the References section at the end using link reference format.\n\n# Notes\n\n- **CRITICAL**: NEVER generate URLs on your own. All URLs must come from search tool results. This is a mandatory requirement. **Any fabricated URL will be considered a severe error.**\n- **MANDATORY**: Always start with a web search. Do not rely on your internal knowledge.\n- Always verify the relevance and credibility of the information gathered.\n- If no URL is provided, focus solely on the search results.\n- Never do any math or any file operations.\n- Do not try to interact with the page. The crawl tool can only be used to crawl content.\n- Do not perform any mathematical calculations.\n- Do not attempt any file operations.\n- Proactively invoke `crawl_tool` when search result summaries are insufficient or when detailed data is needed for analysis.\n- Always include source attribution for all information. This is critical for the final report\'s citations.\n- When presenting information from multiple sources, clearly indicate which source each piece of information comes from.\n- Include images using `![Image Description](image_url)` in a separate section.\n- The included images should **only** be from the information gathered **from the search results or the crawled content**. **Never** include images that are not from the search results or the crawled content.\n- Always use the locale of **en-US** for the output.\n- When time range requirements are specified in the task, strictly adhere to these constraints in your search queries and verify that all information provided falls within the specified time period.', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, id='9693a2c3-60ce-40c1-ae53-ee19de826046'), HumanMessage(content="# Research Topic\n\nScientific Paper Identification Research Plan\n\n# Completed Research Steps\n\n## Completed Step 1: Identify the Journal and Key Research Parameters\n\n<finding>\n# Research Report: Identification of Scientific Paper on System xc- Inhibition in Pulmonary Fibrosis\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThe task is to identify a specific scientific pap